         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot Garden ¶ 20/6/72 ¶  ¶ It is pleasing, dear Mr Bentham, to see you advance so well with the Euphorbiaceae. ¶  It will be a very complete vol that 6th, ¶  more so than the first 2 or 3, as...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">72.06.20a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 45; 1858-70, f. 41</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">20/6/72</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is pleasing, dear Mr Bentham, to see you advance so well with the <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See G. Bentham to M, 10 March 1872.</p>
               </note> It will be a very complete vol that 6th,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> more so than the first 2 or 3, as within the last few years so much was got from N.E. Australia. Indeed I do not think, that many additional species are left to be discovered in Australia.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I shall send off soon the <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name>, which alone will fill a large box. That will be sufficient for finishing the volume, so at least I anticipate. To me it appears a pity that the flora foreruns the genera.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> The latter work is important for the whole world , the former chiefly for Australia, — and so little local interest is evinced in native plants here, that I do not think more than a dozen copies of the work, valuable as it is, were sold in Australia. Poor Harvey's phycology<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Harvey (1858–63).</p>
               </note> fared worse. — I mention this only to show, that there is no reason to overhurry the work. R Brown and Roeper &amp; others have assuredly explained beyond doubt, that the apparently simple flower of <name key="Euphorbia">Euphorbia</name> is in reality a compound one.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Cf. Bentham's remarks in G. Bentham to M, 17 April 1872; see R. Brown (1814), pp. 556-7; Roeper (1824), pp. 9-12.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> Do you really think that the old order of <name key="Urticeae">Urticeae</name> ought to be broke up? If we take it analogous to <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name>, then <name key="Moreae">Moreae</name>, <name key="Artocarpeae">Artocarpeae</name> &amp;c become sections only.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Sponia%20aspera">Sponia aspera</name> is to goats and other pasture animals a deadly poison. This seems not known and might be mentioned in the volume.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No such remark was made in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6, p. 158.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I fully agree in your views about the floral and carpic structures of <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name>, and thus the term achenium must be reserved for the fruit of that order and those closely allied.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Anonymous (1872) reports Bentham's views on the origins of the flower and fruit structures of the <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name>; the complete paper was published as Bentham (1873).</p>
               </note> Dr Steetz, I think, has claims on recognition as working on <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name>. He also regarded, so he said in one of his last letters to me, the researches of Cassini far more important than those of Lessing.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found, but see J. Steetz to M, 27 July 1860 (in this edition as 60-07-27a). </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever your regardful</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I have asked Grisebach to tell me what his <name key="Ophelia%20Baxteri">Ophelia Baxteri</name> is from K.G. Sound<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>WA. M's letter not found.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It seems Dr Sonder never received the 5th vol of the Flora.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Postscripts written in margins of letter.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
